title: For Sale:  1943 Savage Enfield No. 4 Mk I
postcontent: I am selling my 1943 Enfield No. 4 Mk I made my Savage USA for WWII chambered in .303 brit.  I traded an older gentleman for this rifle, which he claims to have brought home from the UK.  He said he made a deal with a Brittish Soldier after the war had ended, and they returned to the UK. There are no import markings....that I can find.  When I asked about actual "combat" he said that he would "suspect it had been involved in the fighting."  The gentleman that provided the rifle, said that he changed nothing, and never actually fired it.  It sat above his mantle for 30-40 years before taking it down and putting it in an ugly padded gun case.  It had sit in the closet for more than 20 years.  To the rifle...  Its serial number is 53C1264, this puts manufacturer in early 1943.  There is still a bit of the british green "corrosion resistant" paint on the rifle and a consiterable amount on the barrel, under the stock.  It is clearly marked US PROPERTY on the side of the reciever, and squared S markins on all metal components.  The rifle functions properly, however, I never fired it.  This has the 2 The only place I have not looked, and dont remember seeing the squared S is on the sight.  It appears that the sight may have been changed to a Mk III sight from the original.  It is pretty much impossible to determine when this happend.  It could have been a "field" upgrade or done when it was imported into England.  I could also have been the original sight, I have seen the same rifle with 3 different types of sights.....I am not an expert!!!  There is an "ER" stamp on the buttstock, and not carved or scratched in.  There are some of these rifles that may "look" better, but most of those have been restored or altered in some way.  This is as it was when it was brought back from the UK 60+ years ago.  I cleaned dust and some furniture wax off of it, but took great care not to damage the finish, original paint, or wood.  There are some dents and dings in the wood, but this is a 73 year old rifle that could very well have been used in combat.  Documentation on these rifles is difficult to acquire.I do not have the bayonette or magazine.  The gentleman I received it from said that he did not have a magazine when he brought it back.  If you have any questions, please let me know.  I will send more detailed pictures if requested, I can only upload 3 pictures, so I just took the 3 that might show a little bit about it.  I could show the rifle in its full length, but that would prohibit any detail from showing.  The darn thing is really long.  This is an opportunity to own a piece of history.

Thus, the barrel can float freely and keeps its point of impact even with the heat generated by a quick succession of shots. By just a few turns, the rifle scope can be detached and reattached within a split second – all without needing to re-zero your optics.
